    detailed: "The federal funds rate is a market rate determined by the supply and demand for overnight reserves, but the Fed influences it through open market operations, the interest rate on reserve balances, and the overnight reverse repo rate. A lower federal funds rate reduces the cost of capital for firms and households, shifting the investment demand curve rightward in the loanable funds market and the AD curve rightward in the goods market. On AP FRQs, students frequently trace this transmission mechanism. During the zero lower bound era (2008-2015 and 2020-2022), the Fed could not lower the rate further and turned to unconventional tools such as quantitative easing. Common mistake: assuming the Fed directly sets the federal funds rate by decree — it operates the rate by adjusting the supply of reserves.",
