    more: "If investors expect inflation to rise by 2 percentage points, lenders will demand a 2-percentage-point higher nominal rate to maintain the same real return. The Fisher effect operates through expectations — it is anticipated inflation, not current inflation, that drives nominal rate adjustments. It implies that central banks cannot permanently lower real interest rates simply by tolerating higher inflation.",
    detailed: "The Fisher equation (nominal rate = real rate + expected inflation) is the algebraic expression of the Fisher effect. In the short run, the real rate can fall if the Fed reduces the nominal rate faster than inflation expectations adjust — this is the transmission mechanism of monetary policy. In the long run, the real rate is determined by real factors (productivity, time preference) and returns to its natural level regardless of monetary policy. On AP FRQs, students apply the Fisher equation and explain how inflation erodes the real return on savings. Common mistake: applying the Fisher effect to the short run — it is a long-run equilibrium result; monetary policy works precisely because short-run inflation expectations are slow to adjust.",
