    more: "Inflation expectations are self-fulfilling: if workers expect higher inflation, they demand higher wages, raising firms' costs and generating the inflation they anticipated. If investors expect higher inflation, they demand higher nominal interest rates through the Fisher effect. Central banks invest heavily in managing expectations through clear communication and consistent policy.",
    detailed: "The Fed's 2% inflation target is explicitly designed to anchor expectations — if the public trusts the Fed will maintain low inflation, wage and price-setting behavior remains moderate even during short-run shocks. Unanchored expectations, as seen in the 1970s, can cause inflation to become entrenched and require a costly disinflation. On AP FRQs, inflation expectations shift the short-run Phillips curve and the SRAS curve: higher expected inflation shifts both upward, raising inflation at every level of unemployment or output. Common mistake: treating inflation expectations as a passive reflection of past inflation — modern macroeconomics emphasizes forward-looking expectations shaped by central bank credibility.",
