    more: "Fiscal policy is set by Congress and the President, not the Federal Reserve. Expansionary fiscal policy (increased spending or tax cuts) shifts AD rightward to close a recessionary gap. Contractionary fiscal policy (reduced spending or tax increases) shifts AD leftward to close an inflationary gap.",
    detailed: "The two main instruments of fiscal policy are government purchases of goods and services (G) and taxes (T). Changes in G have a direct multiplied effect on AD; changes in T work through disposable income and consumption, producing a smaller multiplier. Time lags — recognition, legislative, and implementation — limit fiscal policy's effectiveness as a stabilization tool. On AP FRQs, students calculate the required change in government spending or taxes to close an output gap, applying the expenditure multiplier and tax multiplier. Common mistake: treating transfer payments as a direct component of G in the spending multiplier — transfer payments shift AD only indirectly through consumption, with a smaller multiplier effect than direct government purchases.",
