    more: "Expansionary fiscal policy shifts the AD curve rightward, raising real GDP and the price level. The spending multiplier amplifies the initial injection: a $100 billion increase in government spending raises AD by more than $100 billion. In a recessionary gap, the goal is to restore output to its potential level.",
    detailed: "The required increase in government spending to close a recessionary gap equals the gap divided by the spending multiplier (1 / MPS). Tax cuts require a larger change because the tax multiplier (MPC / MPS) is smaller — households save part of a tax reduction rather than spending it all. Expansionary fiscal policy may generate a budget deficit and increase the national debt. Crowding out can partially offset the stimulus: higher government borrowing raises the real interest rate in the loanable funds market, reducing private investment. On AP FRQs, students calculate the required fiscal action and explain the crowding-out effect. Common mistake: ignoring crowding out — a full analysis of expansionary fiscal policy must acknowledge that higher government borrowing can reduce private investment, partially offsetting the AD stimulus.",
