    detailed: "Closing an inflationary gap requires reducing AD by the size of the gap divided by the relevant multiplier. Higher taxes are contractionary because they reduce disposable income and consumption, but the tax multiplier is smaller in absolute value than the spending multiplier because some of the tax increase comes from reduced saving rather than reduced spending. Contractionary fiscal policy is politically difficult because it involves cutting popular spending programs or raising taxes. On AP FRQs, students draw the inflationary gap on an AD/AS diagram and explain how contractionary policy restores long-run equilibrium at potential output. Common mistake: assuming contractionary fiscal policy always causes a recession — if actual output is above potential, reducing it to potential output closes the inflationary gap without triggering a recession.",
