    more: "The primary US automatic stabilizers are unemployment insurance (payments rise automatically when unemployment increases) and the progressive income tax (tax revenues fall automatically when incomes decline). They cushion the business cycle by maintaining disposable income during downturns and moderating demand growth during booms.",
    detailed: "Automatic stabilizers work without the recognition, legislative, or implementation lags that limit discretionary fiscal policy, making them faster and more reliable stabilizers. They do not eliminate the business cycle but reduce its amplitude. On AP FRQs, students must distinguish automatic stabilizers from discretionary policy — automatic stabilizers are built into existing law and activate without new legislation; discretionary policy requires Congress to act. A recession that expands unemployment insurance payments and reduces tax revenue worsens the budget balance automatically — this is not a policy choice but a built-in response. Common mistake: treating all government spending that rises during a recession as discretionary — much of the increase is automatic and requires no policy decision.",
