    more: "Discretionary policy includes stimulus packages, infrastructure spending bills, tax cuts, and austerity budgets. Unlike automatic stabilizers, it requires legislative action and is subject to political constraints and time lags. The 2009 American Recovery and Reinvestment Act and the 2020 CARES Act are prominent examples of large-scale discretionary fiscal stimulus.",
    detailed: "Three lags limit the effectiveness of discretionary fiscal policy: the recognition lag (time to identify the problem), the legislative lag (time for Congress to pass legislation), and the implementation lag (time for spending to reach the economy). By the time stimulus spending arrives, the recession may have ended, potentially adding to inflationary pressure. Supply-side economists argue that tax cuts that improve incentives can raise long-run potential output rather than simply shifting short-run AD. On AP FRQs, students must explain the lags and evaluate the effectiveness of discretionary fiscal policy as a stabilization tool. Common mistake: ignoring political and logistical constraints — in theory, discretionary policy can precisely close any output gap; in practice, lags and political disagreement make precision nearly impossible.",
