    more: "A budget deficit requires the government to borrow, adding to the national debt. Deficits tend to increase during recessions (automatic stabilizers reduce tax revenue and raise spending) and decrease during expansions. Cyclical deficits reflect the state of the business cycle; structural deficits persist even at full employment.",
    detailed: "Persistent deficits raise concerns about crowding out: government borrowing in the loanable funds market increases the real interest rate, reducing private investment. In the long run, high deficits and debt can slow growth by crowding out capital formation. However, deficits during recessions may be stabilizing — the counterfactual of fiscal austerity can deepen the downturn. On AP FRQs, students must distinguish between a deficit caused by discretionary stimulus (a policy choice) and one caused by automatic stabilizers (a mechanical response to the business cycle). Common mistake: treating all budget deficits as equally harmful — a deficit during a deep recession with low interest rates has different consequences than a structural deficit at full employment.",
