    brief: "The total accumulated stock of government borrowing outstanding at a given point in time.",
    more: "The national debt grows whenever the government runs a budget deficit and shrinks when it runs a surplus. It is typically measured relative to GDP — the debt-to-GDP ratio — to assess sustainability. A rising debt-to-GDP ratio may crowd out private investment, raise future tax burdens, and, if extreme, undermine confidence in government solvency.",
    detailed: "The US national debt is held partly by the public (households, corporations, foreign governments) and partly by other government agencies such as the Social Security Trust Fund. Debt held by the public has more macroeconomic relevance because it competes with private borrowers in the loanable funds market. On AP FRQs, students must distinguish between the deficit (a flow — how much is borrowed in a given year) and the debt (a stock — the cumulative total). A government can run deficits for many years, each adding to the stock of debt. Common mistake: conflating the deficit and the debt — reducing the deficit means borrowing less each year but does not reduce the outstanding debt unless a surplus is achieved.",
    seeAlso: ["budget-deficit", "budget-surplus", "crowding-out", "fiscal-policy"],
