    brief: "Actions by the Federal Reserve to influence the money supply and interest rates in order to achieve macroeconomic goals.",
    more: "The Fed's dual mandate is maximum employment and stable prices (2% inflation). Expansionary monetary policy lowers the federal funds rate, stimulating borrowing, investment, and aggregate demand. Contractionary monetary policy raises the federal funds rate, cooling demand and inflation. Monetary policy operates faster than fiscal policy and avoids legislative delays.",
    detailed: "The transmission mechanism of monetary policy runs from Fed action to the federal funds rate to other interest rates to investment and consumer spending to aggregate demand to real GDP and the price level. On AP FRQs, students draw the money market showing the effect of an OMO on the nominal interest rate, then show the resulting shift in AD and the new macroeconomic equilibrium. A key advantage of monetary policy over fiscal policy is speed — the FOMC meets eight times per year and can act without congressional approval. Common mistake: assuming monetary policy affects the economy instantaneously — in practice, monetary policy operates with variable and uncertain lags of six to eighteen months.",
