    brief: "Federal Reserve actions that increase the money supply and lower interest rates to stimulate aggregate demand.",
    more: "The Fed implements expansionary monetary policy by purchasing government securities in the open market, reducing the reserve requirement, or lowering the discount rate. These actions increase bank reserves, expand the money supply, lower the federal funds rate, reduce borrowing costs, and stimulate investment and consumption. The result is a rightward shift in AD.",
    detailed: "The full chain on AP FRQs: Fed buys bonds (OMO) → bank reserves increase → money supply increases → federal funds rate falls → investment increases → AD shifts right → real GDP and price level rise. This sequence may be tested across multiple linked diagrams: money market, loanable funds market, and AD/AS. Expansionary monetary policy is used to close recessionary gaps. At the zero lower bound, conventional expansionary policy is exhausted and the Fed must resort to unconventional tools (quantitative easing, forward guidance). Common mistake: stopping the chain at the interest rate — AP FRQs require students to trace the full sequence through to real GDP and the price level.",
