    more: "The Fed implements contractionary policy by selling government securities, raising the discount rate, or increasing the reserve requirement. These actions reduce bank reserves, contract the money supply, raise the federal funds rate, increase borrowing costs, and reduce investment and consumption. The result is a leftward shift in AD.",
    detailed: "Contractionary monetary policy is used to close inflationary gaps. The full chain: Fed sells bonds → bank reserves decrease → money supply falls → federal funds rate rises → investment falls → AD shifts left → real GDP falls toward potential and price level decreases. This sequence is the mirror image of expansionary policy. The Fed conducted aggressive contractionary policy in 1979-1982 under Paul Volcker to break double-digit inflation, accepting a deep recession as the price of restoring price stability. On AP FRQs, students draw both the money market and AD/AS showing the effect. Common mistake: failing to show both the money market effect (interest rate rises) and the AD/AS effect (output falls, price level falls) — both diagrams are typically required.",
