    brief: "A monetary policy framework in which the central bank commits to achieving a specific publicly announced inflation rate.",
    more: "The Federal Reserve adopted a formal 2% inflation target in 2012 and reaffirmed it with its flexible average inflation targeting (FAIT) framework in 2020. Clear targets anchor inflation expectations, reduce uncertainty, and enhance central bank credibility and accountability. Most major central banks operate some form of inflation targeting.",
    detailed: "Inflation targeting works through the expectations channel: if the public believes the central bank will act to keep inflation at 2%, wage and price-setting behavior incorporates this expectation, making low inflation self-fulfilling. The Fed's 2020 FAIT framework added flexibility by allowing inflation to run modestly above 2% after periods below target, to achieve average 2% inflation over time. On AP FRQs, inflation targeting is relevant when discussing the role of expectations in the short-run Phillips curve — if the target is credible, expected inflation remains anchored at 2% regardless of short-run shocks. Common mistake: treating inflation targeting as a rigid rule that prevents any deviation — in practice, the target provides a medium-run anchor while allowing short-run flexibility in response to supply shocks.",
