    term: "Phillips Curve",
    brief: "A graphical representation of the relationship between the inflation rate and the unemployment rate.",
    more: "The original Phillips curve showed an empirical inverse relationship: lower unemployment was associated with higher inflation. This suggested policymakers faced a tradeoff — they could choose lower unemployment at the cost of higher inflation, or lower inflation at the cost of higher unemployment.",
    detailed: "The apparent tradeoff broke down in the 1970s when both inflation and unemployment rose simultaneously (stagflation), leading to the development of the short-run and long-run Phillips curve distinction. In the short run, a tradeoff exists because firms and workers have fixed wage and price expectations. In the long run, expectations adjust, and the economy returns to the natural rate of unemployment regardless of inflation. On AP FRQs, students must draw both curves and explain how an adverse supply shock shifts the short-run Phillips curve upward, generating stagflation without a tradeoff. Common mistake: assuming the Phillips curve tradeoff is permanent — it exists only in the short run when expectations are fixed; in the long run, policymakers face no sustainable output-inflation tradeoff.",
    seeAlso: ["short-run-phillips-curve", "long-run-phillips-curve", "natural-rate-of-unemployment", "stagflation"],
