    term: "Short-Run Phillips Curve",
    brief: "A downward-sloping curve showing the inverse relationship between inflation and unemployment when inflation expectations are fixed.",
    more: "Along the short-run Phillips curve, expansionary policy that reduces unemployment raises inflation, and contractionary policy that raises unemployment lowers inflation. The curve is drawn for a given level of expected inflation — it shifts upward when expected inflation rises and downward when it falls.",
    detailed: "The short-run Phillips curve is the mirror image of the AD/AS model in employment-inflation space: moving along the SRPC toward lower unemployment corresponds to moving rightward along the AD curve into an inflationary gap. A supply shock (rising oil prices, for instance) shifts the SRPC upward — at every unemployment rate, inflation is higher. This produces stagflation: rising inflation and rising unemployment simultaneously. On AP FRQs, students draw the SRPC and show how demand-management policy moves the economy along the curve, while supply shocks shift it. Common mistake: treating a shift in the SRPC as a movement along it — an increase in expected inflation shifts the entire curve upward, it does not move the economy to a different point on the same curve.",
    seeAlso: ["phillips-curve", "long-run-phillips-curve", "inflation-expectations", "stagflation"],
