    term: "Long-Run Phillips Curve",
    brief: "A vertical line at the natural rate of unemployment, showing that in the long run there is no tradeoff between inflation and unemployment.",
    more: "In the long run, workers and firms adjust their expectations to actual inflation. Any attempt to hold unemployment below the natural rate generates accelerating inflation as expectations spiral upward. The economy always returns to the natural rate, regardless of the inflation rate — making the long-run Phillips curve vertical.",
    detailed: "The vertical LRPC corresponds to the vertical LRAS curve in AD/AS — both reflect the economy's self-correction mechanism through expectations adjustment. If the Fed attempts to exploit the short-run tradeoff by maintaining unemployment below the natural rate, it triggers an expectations-driven upward shift of the SRPC, requiring ever-higher inflation to sustain the lower unemployment. This accelerationist argument, associated with Milton Friedman and Edmund Phelps, explained the stagflation of the 1970s and is central to modern monetary policy thinking. On AP FRQs, students draw the LRPC at NAIRU and explain why it is vertical. Common mistake: drawing the LRPC with a slope — it must be perfectly vertical at the natural rate of unemployment.",
