    brief: "The unemployment rate consistent with stable inflation, comprising frictional and structural unemployment but not cyclical unemployment.",
    more: "The natural rate is not zero — some unemployment is always present as workers search for jobs and as structural mismatches occur between skills and available positions. It is the unemployment rate at which the economy is at full employment and producing at its potential output. Cyclical unemployment drives the actual rate above the natural rate during recessions.",
    detailed: "The natural rate is not fixed — it changes over time with demographics, technology, job-matching efficiency, and labor market institutions. Extended unemployment insurance can raise the natural rate by reducing job search intensity; improved job matching platforms can lower it. On AP FRQs, the natural rate corresponds to the economy's potential output on the AD/AS diagram and to the NAIRU on the Phillips curve. At the natural rate, there is no recessionary or inflationary gap. Common mistake: equating the natural rate with zero unemployment — the natural rate is the lowest sustainable rate without accelerating inflation, which in practice is well above zero.",
