    more: "NAIRU is operationally equivalent to the natural rate of unemployment. If unemployment falls below NAIRU, inflation accelerates as labor markets tighten and workers gain bargaining power. If unemployment rises above NAIRU, inflation decelerates. The Fed uses estimates of NAIRU to assess inflationary pressure.",
    detailed: "NAIRU is unobservable — it must be estimated from macroeconomic data and carries significant uncertainty. Estimates for the US have shifted over time, falling in the 1990s as the economy sustained low unemployment without inflation and rising during periods of structural labor market disruption. On AP FRQs, NAIRU is the unemployment rate at which the economy sits on the long-run Phillips curve — there is no upward or downward pressure on inflation. Errors in estimating NAIRU have led to policy mistakes in both directions. Common mistake: treating NAIRU as a precise, fixed number — it is an estimate of a moving target, subject to revision as labor market conditions evolve.",
