    group: "Stabilization Policy",
    term: "Supply-Side Policy",
    brief: "Government policies aimed at increasing the economy's productive capacity by shifting aggregate supply and LRAS rightward.",
    more: "Supply-side policies include tax incentives for investment and entrepreneurship, deregulation, investment in education and infrastructure, trade liberalization, and policies promoting research and development. Unlike demand-side policies, they aim to raise potential output rather than close an existing output gap. Success raises real GDP without generating inflation.",
    detailed: "Supply-side policies work through the LRAS curve: if successful, they shift LRAS rightward, raising potential output and lowering the natural rate of unemployment. The Laffer curve is often invoked to argue that lower tax rates can raise tax revenue by stimulating growth — though the empirical evidence for this at current US tax rates is limited. On AP FRQs, supply-side policies are distinguished from demand-side fiscal policy: demand-side changes shift AD, raising output and the price level; supply-side changes shift LRAS, raising output while holding or reducing the price level. Common mistake: assuming all tax cuts are supply-side policy — only cuts that demonstrably improve incentives to work, invest, or innovate qualify; cuts that simply boost disposable income are demand-side.",
