    more: "At a 0% tax rate, revenue is zero. At a 100% rate, revenue is also zero because no one would work. In between, revenue first rises and then falls. Supply-side economists use the Laffer curve to argue that reducing high tax rates can stimulate growth and potentially increase revenue.",
    detailed: "The Laffer curve's key insight is that the relationship between tax rates and revenue is non-linear. However, the revenue-maximizing tax rate is unknown and likely varies by country, time period, and type of tax. Empirical tests of supply-side tax cuts in the US — notably the 1981 Reagan cuts and the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act — have generally not shown self-financing effects at prevailing tax rates. On AP FRQs, the Laffer curve is relevant when evaluating supply-side economics and the claim that tax cuts can pay for themselves. Students must acknowledge its theoretical validity while noting the empirical uncertainty about where the economy sits on the curve. Common mistake: assuming any tax cut increases revenue — this only holds if the economy is on the right-hand (downward-sloping) side of the Laffer curve, which requires very high initial tax rates.",
