    term: "Tax Multiplier",
    brief: "The ratio of the change in equilibrium output to the change in taxes that caused it.",
    more: "The tax multiplier equals -MPC / MPS (negative because a tax increase reduces income, consumption, and output). It is smaller in absolute value than the spending multiplier (1 / MPS) because households save part of a tax reduction rather than spending it entirely. A $100 billion tax cut raises GDP by less than a $100 billion increase in government spending.",
    detailed: "If MPC = 0.8, the spending multiplier is 5 and the tax multiplier is -4. To close the same recessionary gap, a tax cut must be larger than an equivalent increase in government spending. On AP FRQs, students calculate the required change in taxes to close an output gap: required tax change = output gap / tax multiplier. The balanced budget multiplier shows that equal increases in G and T raise GDP by 1 — the spending multiplier effect dominates the tax multiplier effect. Common mistake: applying the spending multiplier to tax changes — tax cuts work through disposable income and consumption, not directly through aggregate demand, giving them a smaller multiplier.",
