    more: "If government spending rises by $100 billion and taxes rise by $100 billion (leaving the deficit unchanged), real GDP increases by $100 billion — a multiplier of 1. This occurs because the spending multiplier exceeds the tax multiplier in absolute value: the government's full spending injection enters the circular flow, while the tax increase is partially absorbed by reduced saving.",
    detailed: "The balanced budget multiplier of 1 holds under simple Keynesian assumptions. In practice, it varies with the composition of spending and taxes, the state of the economy, and the openness of the economy. On AP FRQs, students may be asked to explain why a balanced budget expansion still raises GDP — the key is that the government spending multiplier (1/MPS) exceeds the tax multiplier (MPC/MPS) by exactly 1, so the net effect on AD equals the change in spending. Common mistake: assuming a balanced budget expansion has zero effect on GDP — the spending and tax effects do not cancel because they operate through different channels with different multipliers.",
