    curricula: ["ap-economics"],
    group: "Stabilization Policy",
    term: "Time Lags in Policy",
    brief: "The delays between the need for a policy action and its effect on the economy, which limit the effectiveness of stabilization policy.",
    more: "Three lags affect fiscal policy: the recognition lag (identifying the problem), the legislative lag (passing the law), and the implementation lag (spending reaching the economy). Monetary policy avoids the legislative lag — the FOMC can act every six weeks — but still faces an implementation lag of six to eighteen months before rate changes fully affect output and prices.",
    detailed: "Time lags create the risk of procyclical policy — stimulus that arrives after the recession has ended can worsen inflation, and tightening that arrives after the economy has slowed can deepen a downturn. Automatic stabilizers largely avoid these problems because they respond instantaneously to economic conditions. On AP FRQs, students evaluate fiscal and monetary policy effectiveness by identifying which lags apply and how they limit the ability to fine-tune the economy. The longer and more uncertain the lags, the stronger the case for rules-based policy (such as inflation targeting) over discretionary intervention. Common mistake: assuming monetary policy is immune to lags — the legislative lag is absent, but the implementation lag is substantial and variable, making timing monetary policy precisely very difficult.",
