    group: "Stabilization Policy",
    term: "Zero Lower Bound",
    brief: "The constraint that prevents the nominal interest rate from falling below zero, limiting the effectiveness of conventional monetary policy in severe downturns.",
    more: "When the federal funds rate reaches zero, the Fed cannot cut further using conventional tools. This was the situation in the US from 2008 to 2015 and again in 2020. Unconventional tools — quantitative easing (large-scale asset purchases), forward guidance, and negative interest rate policy — attempt to provide additional stimulus when conventional policy is exhausted.",
    detailed: "The zero lower bound creates a liquidity trap: with interest rates at zero, increases in the money supply may fail to stimulate spending because people are indifferent between holding cash and bonds (both yield zero). Fiscal policy becomes relatively more important when monetary policy is constrained at the zero lower bound. On AP FRQs, students explain why the ZLB limits the Fed's response to a severe recessionary gap and identify alternative policy tools (QE, forward guidance, fiscal stimulus). Common mistake: assuming the zero lower bound applies to all interest rates — some central banks have implemented negative deposit rates, and some market interest rates have turned negative, suggesting the true lower bound may be slightly below zero.",
