    more: "Unemployment imposes costs on individuals (lost income, skill erosion, psychological harm) and on society (lost output, increased government expenditure on benefits). The three main types are frictional, structural, and cyclical. Only cyclical unemployment represents a macroeconomic problem requiring policy intervention.",
    detailed: "The official unemployment rate, published monthly by the Bureau of Labor Statistics, counts only those without a job who are actively looking for work. It therefore undercounts true labor market slack — discouraged workers (who have stopped searching) and those working part-time who want full-time work are excluded. The U-6 measure, which includes these groups, is broader. On AP FRQs, students identify which type of unemployment is present, explain its cause, and recommend appropriate policy. Frictional and structural unemployment are inevitable; cyclical unemployment is the target of stabilization policy. Common mistake: concluding that falling unemployment is always positive — unemployment can fall because discouraged workers exit the labor force rather than because more people are finding jobs.",
