    more: "Frictional unemployment is a normal feature of a healthy labor market — it reflects the time required for job matching rather than a lack of available jobs. It includes recent graduates entering the workforce, workers between jobs, and those relocating for new opportunities. Better job-matching platforms and information reduce frictional unemployment.",
    detailed: "Frictional unemployment contributes to the natural rate of unemployment and is present even at full employment. It is not a target for demand-side policy — expansionary fiscal or monetary policy cannot eliminate the time required to match workers with vacancies. Supply-side interventions such as improved job boards, retraining programs, and relocation subsidies can reduce frictional unemployment by improving matching efficiency. On AP FRQs, students distinguish frictional from structural unemployment — frictional workers have skills employers want but need time to find the right job; structural workers lack the skills currently in demand. Common mistake: trying to eliminate frictional unemployment through stimulus — this type of unemployment is the irreducible result of search and matching in a dynamic labor market.",
