    more: "Structural unemployment arises from technological change, industry decline, and geographic shifts in employment. A coal miner whose skill set has no application in a technology-driven economy is structurally unemployed. It is part of the natural rate of unemployment and requires supply-side solutions — retraining, education, and geographic mobility assistance.",
    detailed: "Unlike frictional unemployment, structural unemployment cannot be resolved simply through more search time — the worker lacks the qualifications employers require. Automation, globalization, and sectoral shifts continuously generate structural unemployment in some industries while creating demand for new skills elsewhere. On AP FRQs, students must correctly identify structural unemployment as a natural-rate phenomenon and recommend appropriate supply-side policies rather than demand management. Contractionary sectors in the US — manufacturing, coal, retail — have generated significant structural unemployment that persistent demand stimulus cannot address. Common mistake: treating structural unemployment as cyclical and recommending expansionary AD policy — boosting demand cannot bridge a skills mismatch.",
