    more: "Cyclical unemployment rises during recessions as firms reduce production and lay off workers, and falls during expansions as demand recovers. It is directly linked to the output gap — a recessionary gap generates cyclical unemployment. It is the primary target of stabilization policy and the type addressed by expansionary fiscal or monetary policy.",
    detailed: "Cyclical unemployment does not contribute to the natural rate — it is excess unemployment above the natural rate caused by insufficient aggregate demand. On AD/AS diagrams, cyclical unemployment corresponds to the recessionary gap: actual output falls short of potential, meaning the economy is not utilizing all available workers. Okun's Law quantifies this relationship — each additional percentage point of cyclical unemployment is associated with approximately a 2% shortfall in real GDP relative to potential. On AP FRQs, students use cyclical unemployment to motivate expansionary policy and trace the full chain through to real GDP recovery. Common mistake: treating all unemployment as cyclical — without identifying the type, students cannot select the correct policy response.",
