    detailed: "A falling unemployment rate does not always signal improvement — if discouraged workers exit the labor force rather than finding jobs, unemployment falls while employment stagnates. The labor force participation rate provides a complementary measure. On AP FRQs, students calculate the unemployment rate given employment and labor force data and explain the relationship between cyclical unemployment and the output gap via Okun's Law. The unemployment rate feeds directly into the Phillips curve — lower unemployment is associated with higher inflation along the short-run Phillips curve. Common mistake: treating a declining unemployment rate as unambiguously positive without checking whether it reflects job gains or labor force exit.",
