    more: "The labor force excludes those under 16, institutionalized individuals, active-duty military, and those not actively seeking work (retirees, students, homemakers, discouraged workers). Changes in the size of the labor force affect the unemployment rate independently of actual job creation. A growing labor force can push up the unemployment rate even if employment is rising.",
    detailed: "The labor force is the denominator of the unemployment rate — changes in its size affect the rate even without changes in employment. During the COVID-19 pandemic, millions exited the labor force, reducing the measured unemployment rate even before significant rehiring occurred. On AP FRQs, students are expected to understand that the labor force is not fixed and that demographic changes, retirement waves, and economic discouragement can shift its size. Labor force growth is also a source of long-run economic growth — more workers available increases potential output. Common mistake: assuming a falling unemployment rate means more people are working — it could mean fewer people are counted in the labor force.",
