    detailed: "US labor force participation peaked around 67% in 2000, declined through the 2000s and 2010s due to aging demographics and discouraged workers, and fell sharply during the COVID-19 pandemic. A below-trend LFPR represents potential labor supply that is not being tapped, acting as a headwind on growth. On AP FRQs, students may be asked to explain why falling unemployment and declining LFPR can occur simultaneously, and what this implies about true labor market slack. Common mistake: using the unemployment rate alone to assess the health of the labor market — the LFPR is an essential complement that captures workers who are outside the labor force entirely.",
