    more: "In a competitive labor market, a minimum wage set above the equilibrium wage creates a surplus of labor (unemployment) because the quantity of labor supplied exceeds the quantity demanded at the higher wage. The size of the employment effect depends on the elasticity of labor supply and demand and how far the minimum wage exceeds the market wage.",
    detailed: "The employment effects of the minimum wage are empirically contested. Card and Krueger's 1994 study found minimal employment loss from a state-level minimum wage increase, suggesting labor markets may have monopsonistic features that reduce the simple competitive prediction. Subsequent research has found mixed results — the employment effect appears small at modest increases but larger when the minimum wage rises substantially above local market wages. On AP FRQs, students draw a labor market diagram showing the surplus created by a binding minimum wage and identify the resulting unemployment. Common mistake: assuming a minimum wage always substantially reduces employment — in monopsonistic markets, a minimum wage can increase both wages and employment.",
