    brief: "Wages paid above the market-clearing level to increase worker productivity, reduce turnover, and attract higher-quality applicants.",
    more: "Firms may voluntarily pay above-equilibrium wages because higher pay raises worker effort (reducing shirking), lowers costly turnover, and attracts more productive applicants. This makes above-market wages rational from the firm's perspective even without union pressure or minimum wage laws. Henry Ford's $5-a-day wage in 1914 is a classic example.",
    detailed: "Efficiency wages contribute to wage stickiness — firms are reluctant to cut wages during downturns because doing so would reduce morale, effort, and worker quality, potentially raising unit labor costs even as the wage bill falls. This helps explain why wages do not fall sufficiently to clear labor markets during recessions, generating involuntary unemployment. On AP FRQs, efficiency wages are a microeconomic explanation for labor market rigidity and can be used to explain why unemployment persists even in the absence of formal wage floors. Common mistake: assuming efficiency wages are always beneficial — they raise per-worker productivity but may reduce total employment by keeping wages above the market-clearing level.",
