    term: "Monopsony",
    brief: "A labor market in which there is a single buyer of labor, giving the employer significant wage-setting power.",
    more: "In a monopsonistic labor market, the employer faces the full market supply of labor and must raise wages to attract additional workers. This causes the marginal cost of labor to exceed the wage rate, leading the monopsonist to hire fewer workers at a lower wage than would occur in a competitive market. Company towns historically exemplified monopsony.",
    detailed: "Unlike competitive markets, monopsonistic employers operate below the competitive employment level and pay below-competitive wages, creating a deadweight loss. A minimum wage in a monopsony market can increase both wages and employment up to the competitive level — this insight explains why empirical studies sometimes find minimal employment loss from minimum wage increases in concentrated labor markets. On AP FRQs, students draw the monopsonist's labor market diagram showing the MRC (marginal resource cost) curve above the supply curve and the profit-maximizing wage and employment level. Common mistake: assuming all labor markets are competitive — significant employer concentration in certain industries and geographic areas means monopsony power is an empirically relevant phenomenon.",
