    brief: "The way in which total income in an economy is divided among individuals, households, or groups.",
    more: "Income distribution is commonly measured using the Lorenz curve and the Gini coefficient. A perfectly equal distribution produces a straight 45-degree Lorenz curve and a Gini coefficient of 0; complete inequality produces a Gini of 1. US income inequality has risen significantly since the 1970s, driven by skill-biased technological change, globalization, and declining unionization.",
    detailed: "The Lorenz curve plots the cumulative share of income received by the bottom x% of the population. The Gini coefficient equals the area between the Lorenz curve and the line of perfect equality, divided by the total area below the equality line. Government redistribution through progressive taxation and transfer payments compresses the post-tax, post-transfer income distribution relative to the pre-tax distribution. On AP FRQs, students draw and interpret the Lorenz curve and explain how progressive taxation shifts it toward greater equality. Common mistake: conflating income inequality with poverty — inequality measures relative shares, while poverty measures whether incomes fall below an absolute or relative threshold.",
