    more: "Tariffs raise the domestic price of the imported good, reducing imports and expanding domestic production. They generate government revenue and benefit domestic producers at the expense of domestic consumers, who pay higher prices. The net welfare effect is negative because the gains to producers and government are smaller than the losses to consumers.",
    detailed: "On an AP FRQ supply-and-demand diagram, a tariff raises the domestic price from the world price to the tariff-inclusive price. Domestic production expands, domestic consumption contracts, imports shrink, and a deadweight loss triangle appears (two triangles — one representing the production inefficiency, one the consumption distortion). The government collects a tariff revenue rectangle. Retaliatory tariffs from trading partners can reduce export markets, partially or fully offsetting the intended protection. Common mistake: treating tariffs as purely beneficial to the domestic economy — while producers gain, consumers lose more, and the net welfare effect is negative in most cases.",
