    more: "Like a tariff, a quota raises the domestic price of the imported good by restricting supply, benefiting domestic producers and harming domestic consumers. Unlike a tariff, the government collects no revenue — instead, quota rents accrue to foreign exporters (if they hold the licenses) or domestic importers (if the government auctions the licenses). The welfare losses are similar in structure to a tariff.",
    detailed: "A quota analysis looks similar to a tariff diagram — domestic price rises above world price, domestic production expands, domestic consumption falls, and deadweight loss triangles appear. The key difference is the revenue rectangle: with a tariff it goes to the government; with a quota it becomes a quota rent, potentially flowing to foreign sellers. On AP FRQs, students compare tariffs and quotas in terms of their effects on price, quantity, domestic production, imports, and government revenue. Both are trade barriers that reduce the gains from trade. Common mistake: assuming tariffs and quotas are equivalent in all respects — the revenue distribution differs, and quotas are inflexible in response to demand shifts, potentially allowing imports to rise less than intended if demand falls.",
