    term: "Balance of Payments",
    brief: "A comprehensive record of all economic transactions between a country's residents and the rest of the world during a given period.",
    more: "The balance of payments consists of two main accounts: the current account (trade in goods, services, income, and transfers) and the financial account (investment flows). By accounting identity, the two accounts sum to zero — any current account deficit must be financed by a corresponding financial account surplus. The balance of payments always balances.",
    detailed: "A current account deficit means a country imports more than it exports (on a broad measure) and must borrow from abroad or sell assets to finance the shortfall. A financial account surplus (foreign investment into the country) funds this deficit. On AP FRQs, students must explain the relationship between the current account and financial account and trace how an exchange rate change affects trade flows and the current account balance. The US has run persistent current account deficits since the 1980s, financed by large financial account inflows. Common mistake: treating a current account deficit as inherently problematic — it reflects a shortfall in domestic saving relative to investment, which may be appropriate if the country is attracting productive foreign investment.",
