    more: "The current account balance equals exports minus imports of goods and services, plus net income from abroad (wages, dividends, interest) and net current transfers (foreign aid, remittances). A current account surplus means a country earns more from abroad than it pays; a deficit means the reverse. The US typically runs a current account deficit, primarily driven by its goods trade deficit.",
    detailed: "A current account deficit implies that domestic investment exceeds domestic saving — the economy borrows from abroad to finance investment beyond what can be funded domestically. On AP FRQs, students trace the effect of a currency depreciation on the current account: a weaker dollar makes US exports cheaper and imports more expensive, improving the trade balance and moving the current account toward surplus, though the J-curve effect predicts that the improvement may be delayed as existing contracts adjust. Common mistake: equating the current account exclusively with the goods trade balance — services trade (tourism, education, finance) and income flows are significant components.",
