    detailed: "Foreign direct investment (FDI) — buying controlling stakes in foreign companies or building facilities — and portfolio investment — buying foreign stocks and bonds — are the main components. When the US runs a current account deficit, foreigners accumulate dollar-denominated assets (Treasury bonds, equities, real estate) — this is the US financial account surplus. On AP FRQs, students must understand the accounting identity and explain why a trade deficit corresponds to net capital inflows. Common mistake: treating a financial account surplus as inherently positive — it simply reflects the mirror of a current account deficit and means the country is borrowing from abroad.",
