    more: "A higher exchange rate means the domestic currency is worth more in terms of foreign currency — it has appreciated. Exchange rates affect the relative prices of exports and imports: a stronger dollar makes US exports more expensive for foreigners and imports cheaper for US consumers, tending to worsen the trade balance. A weaker dollar does the reverse.",
    detailed: "In the foreign exchange market, the demand for a currency comes from foreigners wanting to buy domestic goods, services, and assets; the supply comes from domestic residents buying foreign goods, services, and assets. On AP FRQs, students draw the foreign exchange market and show how a change in interest rates, income, or inflation shifts supply or demand and changes the exchange rate. Higher US interest rates attract foreign investment, increasing demand for dollars and appreciating the dollar. Common mistake: confusing the direction of exchange rate effects — an appreciated currency hurts exports (making them pricier abroad) and benefits importers, which is the opposite of what many assume.",
