    more: "When a currency appreciates, it buys more foreign currency than before. This makes imports cheaper (benefiting domestic consumers) and exports more expensive abroad (hurting domestic exporters). An appreciating currency is associated with higher domestic interest rates, stronger economic growth, or lower domestic inflation relative to trading partners.",
    detailed: "On AP FRQs, currency appreciation is typically triggered by a rise in domestic interest rates: higher rates attract foreign capital, increasing demand for the dollar in the foreign exchange market and raising its value. The appreciation then makes exports more expensive and imports cheaper, shifting the current account toward deficit. Students must trace the chain from monetary policy to interest rates to capital flows to exchange rate to trade balance. Common mistake: assuming currency appreciation is always favorable — while it reduces import costs, it simultaneously harms export-oriented industries and can worsen the current account deficit.",
