    more: "When a currency depreciates, it buys less foreign currency. Imports become more expensive for domestic consumers, and exports become cheaper for foreign buyers. Depreciation tends to improve the trade balance over time by reducing imports and boosting exports, though the J-curve effect means the current account may worsen initially before improving.",
    detailed: "Currency depreciation is often associated with lower domestic interest rates, weaker economic growth, or higher domestic inflation. Expansionary monetary policy that lowers the federal funds rate reduces the return on dollar-denominated assets, reducing foreign demand for dollars, depreciating the exchange rate, and stimulating exports. On AP FRQs, students must trace this chain from monetary policy through interest rates, exchange rate, and trade balance. Currency depreciation also raises the cost of imported inputs, potentially generating cost-push inflation. Common mistake: treating depreciation as automatically beneficial — while it helps exporters, it raises the cost of imports, including raw materials and consumer goods, which can fuel inflation.",
