    more: "PPP predicts that if a Big Mac costs $5 in the US and the same burger costs 50 pesos in Mexico, the exchange rate should be 10 pesos per dollar. In practice, exchange rates deviate from PPP due to transportation costs, trade barriers, non-tradable goods, and capital flows. PPP is most useful for comparing living standards across countries, not for predicting short-run exchange rate movements.",
    detailed: "The Economist's Big Mac Index is a popularized application of PPP. The World Bank uses PPP-adjusted figures to compare GDP across countries, correcting for differences in price levels — a dollar goes further in a low-income country, so PPP-adjusted incomes there are higher than market exchange rates suggest. On AP FRQs, PPP is relevant when discussing the long-run determinants of exchange rates: countries with higher inflation tend to see their currencies depreciate, consistent with relative PPP. Common mistake: treating PPP as a useful short-run predictor of exchange rates — speculative flows and interest rate differentials dominate exchange rate movements in the short run, making PPP a poor near-term forecasting tool.",
