    more: "A trade deficit means the country is consuming more than it produces domestically and borrowing the difference from abroad. It is financed by a corresponding financial account surplus — foreigners invest in the country to fund the excess of imports over exports. The US has run persistent trade deficits for decades, primarily driven by high consumer demand and relatively low domestic saving.",
    detailed: "The trade balance identity links the current account to saving and investment: current account balance = national saving minus domestic investment. A trade deficit reflects insufficient national saving to fund domestic investment needs, requiring borrowing from abroad. On AP FRQs, students explain how a tax cut that reduces national saving worsens the trade deficit by increasing the gap between investment and saving, drawing in foreign capital and appreciating the currency. Common mistake: treating trade deficits as automatically harmful — a deficit driven by strong investment demand and foreign confidence in the domestic economy is very different from one driven by weak saving and excess consumption.",
