    brief: "International trade conducted without tariffs, quotas, or other government-imposed barriers.",
    more: "Free trade allows countries to specialize in goods and services where they have a comparative advantage, increasing total world output and lowering prices for consumers. Economists broadly support free trade as welfare-enhancing in the aggregate, though it creates winners (consumers, export industries) and losers (import-competing industries and their workers).",
    detailed: "The case for free trade is grounded in comparative advantage — even if one country is more efficient at producing everything, both countries gain from specializing and trading. Free trade agreements such as NAFTA/USMCA and the WTO framework reduce trade barriers multilaterally. On AP FRQs, students evaluate the costs and benefits of free trade: gains from specialization, lower consumer prices, and access to larger markets are weighed against job losses in import-competing sectors and the distributional consequences of trade. Common mistake: concluding that free trade is unambiguously good for all individuals — while it raises aggregate welfare, it redistributes income, and workers in declining sectors may face significant adjustment costs without adequate support.",
